2 Abstract

This report is going to analyze how our perception of temperature based on humidity. To do this we will look into the relationship between three weather factors- Temperature, Apparent Temperature, and Humidity Level. This is an important analysis to look into because as our earth is quickly heating up due to pollution we need to know how these factors really do influence our perception of the temperature and how we can be best prepared to deal with it. The findings could apply to several areas of daily life for many people, especially those who spend long hours outdoors.

3 Introduction

This data set was gathered over the course of 10 years in Szeged, Hungary to measure any relationships between different factors in weather. Living in Oklahoma and being someone who sweats incredibly easy I want to see if I can find a relationship between apparent temperature and humidity. I have always heard that humidity makes it worse so I want to know if this is true.

3.5 What problem do you wish to solve?/ Research Question

Many problems have been outlined and solved by WeatherSparks article on the data but what I want to look at is the effect Humidity has on our Apparent temperature, ie- does humidity make us feel hotter? To do this I will look at the Linear Regression Model for Humidity and Apparent Temperature as well as the Linear Regression Model for Humidity and Temperature. In these comparisons I will be using Temperature as our constant variable, Humidity as our independent variable and Apparent Temperature as our dependent variable. To measure if there is any difference in percieved temperature vs actual I will take the SLR models and compare their beta values. My expectation is that apparent temperature will be higher with higher humidity than actual temperature will be with lower humidity.

4 Theory needed to carry out SLR

Following the graphs above it is appears our Temperature Y-value decreases linearly (with a few outliers) as Humidity increases. The Simple Linear Regression model is described by the following-

\[ y = \beta_0+\beta_1 x + \epsilon\\ \]

For this experiment we will have two cases. The first will describe the controlled case and will use actual temperature as the dependent variable and Humidity as the independent variable as described below-

\[ \textsf{Temperature (C) }= \beta_0 + \beta_1 (\textsf{Humidity}) + \epsilon\\ \] The second case will hold Apparent Temperature as the dependent variable and Humidity as the independant variable-

\[ \textsf{Apparent Temperature (C) }= \beta_0+\beta_1(\textsf{Humidity}) + \epsilon \\ \]

We cannot use a deterministic model because of the wide spread of results but we can use the above Simple Linear Regression Model because it is a type of probabalistic model which can more accurately portray this data set. The idea of a Simple Linear Regression model will lean on the assumption that the mean value of our dependent variable (or our Temperature vars) will make a straight line when graphed and if a point deviates it will be equal to epsilon.

At this point B_0 and B_1 are both unknown to us but we can assume that there will be some negative deviation and some positive deviation so it would be permissable to set the expected value of epsilon_i = 0, and we would have the following-

\[ E(y)=E(\beta_0+\beta_1x_i+ \epsilon_i)\\ = \beta_0+\beta_i x_1 \] Knowing this, we also know that the we can represent the mean of our dependent Temperature for any x with E(Y|x). Furthermore, it will graph linearly by using y-intercept B_0 and a slope B_1.

Our next move is to fit an SLR to the data set. To accomplish this I will need to make estimations for the betas based on the sampling distributions of the estimators and those will depend on the epsilon value.
List of assumptions- Epsilon = 0 The probablity distribution of epsilon is normal Errors are indepentant of one another V(Epsilon)= some constant for all valse of x

5 Estimating The Parameters

The method I will use to estimate B_0 and B_1 is Method of Least Squares with the goal to determine the line that best fits my data set with a minimum sum of squares deviations also known as Sum of Squares for Error. From the earlier discussion we know that- $$

y = _0+_1 x + \ \

(y_i- ) = y_i - ( + x_i)\ ^n_{i=1} (y_i-(+)) = SSE\ $$

6.8 Check Normality

#The shapiro test requires less than 5000 points so I took a random sample of 4999 below
weatherCont1.lm=lm(Humidity~TemperatureC, data=weather)
weatherExp1.lm=lm(Humidity~ApparentTemperatureC, data=weather)

normcheck(weatherCont1.lm, shapiro.wilk = TRUE)

normcheck(weatherExp1.lm, shapiro.wilk = TRUE)

The p-value for the Shapiro-Wilk test is much larger than alpha at <.9. The null hypothesis in this case an would be that the errors are distributed normally:

\[ \epsilon \textsf{~} N(0, \sigma^2) \]

The results of the Shapiro-Wilk test indicate that we do not have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis as implausible (as the p-value 0 is much greater than the standard of comparison, 0.05), leading us to reasonably assume that the data is distributed normally.

6.9 Testing another model for comparison/Validation

Now we need to determine if a linear model is the only option to test. To do this I will test the results against a quadratic curve.

6.9.1 Fitting a quadratic to the points

\[ y_i= \beta_0 + \beta_1x_i +\beta_2x_i^2\\ \]

quad.lm=lm(TemperatureC~Humidity + I(Humidity^2),data=weather)

plot(TemperatureC~Humidity,bg="Blue",pch=21,cex=1.2,
   ylim=c(0,1.1*max(TemperatureC)),xlim=c(0,1.1*max(Humidity)),main="Scatter Plot and Quadratic of TemperatureC vs Humidity",data=weather)
myplot = function(x){quad.lm$coef[1] + quad.lm$coef[2]*x + quad.lm$coef[3]*x^2}
curve(myplot, lwd = 2, add = TRUE)

quad2.lm=lm(ApparentTemperatureC~Humidity + I(Humidity^2),data=weather)

plot(ApparentTemperatureC~Humidity,bg="Blue",pch=21,cex=1.2,
   ylim=c(0,1.1*max(ApparentTemperatureC)),xlim=c(0,1.1*max(Humidity)),main="Scatter Plot and Quadratic of ApparentTemperatureC vs Humidity",data=weather)
myplot = function(x){quad2.lm$coef[1] + quad2.lm$coef[2]*x + quad2.lm$coef[3]*x^2}
curve(myplot, lwd = 2, add = TRUE)

The quadratic did not give very different results. The graph still looks largely linear but we will wait on further analysis to make a final decision.

6.15 Avoiding Bias with Cooks Distance

We must clean our data of outliers as much as possible so that the correct data we present is not skewed. To do this we will use cooks distance to examine outliers and that will more closely examine how data is being skewed by these outliers.

cooks20x(weatherExp1.lm)

Cooks Distance for this linear model and data tells me that observation numbers 37, 48, and 49 have large enough values (>=10) that they are considered significant and need closer examination.

I can make a new model, made from the same linear model, using the same data, but removing the datum with the highest Cooks distance (48) removed:

weatherExp2.lm=lm(ApparentTemperatureC~Humidity, data=weather2[-49,])

7 Conclusion

There did turn out to be a relationship between the Humidity and the Apparent Temperature as well as the Humidity and the real temperature. Going into the project my assumption was that as humidity increased the temperature and apparent temperature would rise as well but the plots from the very beginning proved that to be merely an assumption. The real relationship between either temperature and humidity was a negative linear one, so as humidity grew the temperatures fell.

This is important information to gather becuase how people feel when they are outside will influence everything they do. It will influence whether or not a tourist wants to spend the day shopping or at a pool. It also influences how productive a farmer should anticipate he will be throughout humid parts of the year. The interesting thing found by this data was humidity may actually make the temperature MORE bearable.

7.1 Answer your research question

I had two personal goals going into the assignment. The first was to determine if Humidity caused ApparentTemperature to change compared to the real temperature. Almost immediately I found out the answer was yes. As mentioned above I thought the impact humidity would have on the temperature and the apparent temperature would be a positive linear one but it turned out to be a negative linear one- meaning as humidity decreased, both the Temperature and Apparent Temperature fell. Even early on you could compare the graphs of the two outputs and see Apparent Temperature would fall at a faster rate as humidity was increased an the actual temperature would fall. This was more concrete after the equation of the fitted lines for the two models was developed and we had actual quantitave values to compare. In conclusion, yes humidity influences the apparent air temperature but does not influence it in a way that makes it feel hotter as I had first thought.

7.2 Suggest ways to improve model or experiment

This would probably be the only time that I would ever not recommend using the metric system. With Farenheit the values would be further apart and differences would likely be more apparent. Furthermore, it is usually nice to have a large data set but I think it would have served me better to have found a way to look at how the weather factors had changed over time by looking at the past years but I am not that profficient, yet.
